## The Exhaustion Timeline

```
Pool: 20 connections max | Traffic: 200 req/s | Avg query: 50ms

t=0.000s  ── Request #1 arrives   → pool.connect() → Connection 1 ACQUIRED (never returned)
t=0.005s  ── Request #2 arrives   → pool.connect() → Connection 2 ACQUIRED (never returned)
t=0.010s  ── Request #3 arrives   → pool.connect() → Connection 3 ACQUIRED (never returned)
  ...
t=0.095s  ── Request #20 arrives  → pool.connect() → Connection 20 ACQUIRED (never returned)
                                     ╔══════════════════════════════════════╗
                                     ║   🔴 POOL FULLY EXHAUSTED (0 free)  ║
                                     ╚══════════════════════════════════════╝
t=0.100s  ── Request #21 arrives  → pool.connect() → ⏳ WAITING...
t=0.105s  ── Request #22 arrives  → pool.connect() → ⏳ WAITING...
  ...hundreds more requests queue up...

t=30.00s  ── Nginx upstream timeout → 502 Bad Gateway
t=30.00s  ── PostgreSQL: "too many clients already" (if new pools spawn)
t=30.00s  ── Node.js: "connect ETIMEDOUT" (queued requests time out)
```

With the leak, it only takes **20 requests total** (not 200/s) to permanently kill the API.

## The Fix: Three Levels of Improvement

### Level 1: Immediate Fix — Release the Connection

```javascript
// ✅ FIXED: Always release with try/finally
app.get('/api/users/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const client = await pool.connect();
  try {
    const result = await client.query(
      'SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1',
      [req.params.id]
    );
    res.json(result.rows[0]);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('Query failed:', err);
    res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
  } finally {
    client.release();  // ← ALWAYS returns connection to pool, even on error
  }
});
```

### Level 2: Better — Use pool.query() for Single Queries

```javascript
// ✅ BETTER: pool.query() auto-acquires AND auto-releases
app.get('/api/users/:id', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    // pool.query() internally does: connect → query → release
    const result = await pool.query(
      'SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1',
      [req.params.id]
    );

    if (result.rows.length === 0) {
      return res.status(404).json({ error: 'User not found' });
    }

    res.json(result.rows[0]);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('Query failed:', err);
    res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
  }
});
```

> **Rule of thumb**: Use `pool.query()` for single queries. Only use `pool.connect()` when you need transactions (multiple queries on the same connection).

